The addition of diverse viewpoints and ideas to a group or organization may foster more innovative and successful decision-making, which is just one of the numerous advantages that diversity can provide. Additionally, it may aid in fostering inclusion and minimizing prejudice and discrimination. On the other side, variety may also bring up difficulties including a lack of comprehension of other cultures and backgrounds and communication obstacles. When problem-solving and creativity are crucial, such as in a commercial or research context, diversity is probably most advantageous. Additionally, it is probably advantageous in settings like healthcare or education when a varied population is being serviced. On the other hand, in circumstances when a homogenous group is required for operational efficiency or safety, such as in a military unit or a medical surgical team, variety may be less advantageous. 